<link href="adcp.css" rel="stylesheet"><entry><xh5>smile at someone • smile on someone</xh5><p> <i>smile at someone</i>—(also: smile to someone) look at a person with a smile on one’s face (expressing pleasure or amusement): The waiter brought her a drink. “Just what the doctor ordered,” she said, <u>smiling at</u> him.</p><p> <i>smile on someone—</i>1. <i>(of fate, luck, etc.)</i> be favorable to a person: Good fortune indeed had <u>smiled on</u> the child as she could easily have been placed on one of the other three chain gangs. 2. <i>= smile at someone: </i>The doctor <u>smiled on</u> the child, and, chucking him under the chin, told him he must hate nobody...</p> </entry>
